04020nmm a2200649Ia 9781501731242DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1143617478  a97815017312427 a10.7591/97815017312422doi  a(DE-B1597)534541  a(OCoLC)1141260432  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS228.G45B76 200904a820.93551 aBrown, Judith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGlamour in Six Dimensions :bModernism and the Radiance of Form /cJudith Brown. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b17 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGlamour is an alluring but elusive concept. We most readily associate it with fashion, industrial design, and Hollywood of the Golden Age, and yet it also shaped the language and interests of high modernism. In Glamour in Six Dimensions, Judith Brown looks at the historical and aesthetic roots of glamour in the early decades of the twentieth century, arguing that glamour is the defining aesthetic of modernism. In the clean lines of modernism she finds the ideal conditions for glamour-blankness, polish, impenetrability, and the suspicion of emptiness behind it all.Brown focuses on several cultural products that she argues helped to shape glamour's meanings: the most significant perfume of the twentieth century, Chanel No. 5; the idea of the Jazz Age and its ubiquitous cigarette; the celebrity photograph; the staging of primitivism; and the invention of a shimmering plastic called cellophane. Alongside these artifacts, she takes up the development, refinement, and analysis of glamour in Anglo-American poetry, film, fiction, and drama of the period. Glamour in Six Dimensions thus asks its reader to see the proximity between the vernacular and elite cultures of modernism, and particularly how glamour was animated by artists working at the crossroads of the mundane and the extraordinary: Wallace Stevens, F. Scott Fitzgerald, Virginia Woolf, Josephine Baker, D. H. Lawrence, Gertrude Stein, Nella Larsen, and others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGlamour in literature. 0aGlamourxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aGlamourxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)xSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aModernism (Literature)zGreat Britain. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterary Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173124240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501731242/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles